instance security_and_safety_considerations : DTDFVocab:SecuritySafety [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system leverages MQTT as the primary messaging protocol, implemented via the Mosquitto broker (see [52]). Mosquitto supports secure authentication through username/password credentials and optional client certificates, and enforces strict Access Control Lists (ACLs) at the topic level to restrict publish/subscribe rights. Transport security is achieved using TLS v1.2/v1.3, permitting both server‑side and mutual client‑server TLS authentication, and the broker optionally supports SASL mechanisms (PLAIN, EXTERNAL) to further strengthen the authentication channel. In addition, the system integrates the ThingsBoard 4.0.0 open‑source IoT platform (see [53]), which provides comprehensive security and safety controls: JWT‑based authentication for cloud services, OAuth2 and LDAP integration for enterprise single‑sign‑on, role‑based access control (admin, tenant, customer, gateway) that scopes permissions to specific device groups and dashboards, TLS 1.2+ over HTTPS for all HTTP endpoints and MQTT transport, per‑device client certificates or shared access keys, and detailed audit logs for all connection events, message deliveries, and configuration changes. ThingsBoard also implements fail‑safe mechanisms such as automatic reconnect, message persistence, and keep‑alive timeouts, ensuring reliable operation even under network disruptions. The combination of broker‑level ACLs, TLS encryption, and platform‑level RBAC and audit logging forms a layered security posture that mitigates unauthorized access, data tampering, and eavesdropping, while supporting safety‑critical requirements through deterministic message handling and controlled device access."
]
